## 2026-07-16 — Session 9: design pass — Amplitude-aligned typography, color, chart palette

Token/styling-level restyle toward Amplitude's actual product design (per their public brand guide,
brand.amplitude.com). Scope was tokens + fonts + chart palette ONLY — no component/layout/interaction
changes (the app has been through 8 sessions of QA/review).

**Typography — switched Geist → Poppins.** Amplitude's brand typeface is Gellix (geometric sans, not
free); their OWN documented web substitute is **Poppins** (Google Fonts). Geist was Vercel's scaffold
default and off-brand. `layout.tsx` now loads Poppins (`--font-poppins`, weights 400/500/600/700) as the
sans; `@theme` maps `--font-sans`/`--font-heading` to it. Kept Geist Mono for tabular-numeric spots only
(not part of Amplitude's system). Weight usage already matches Amplitude's (SemiBold titles via the
existing `font-semibold` headings, Regular body, Bold only on the logo mark). **Font decision: Poppins was
kept** — verified running in both themes on a data-dense dashboard; it reads clean/geometric and
professional, not too rounded/friendly, so no need to fall back to Plus Jakarta Sans.

**Color tokens.** Amplitude leads with Blue + Black/White, gray for hierarchy, blue reserved for
CTAs/links/active (not body text/chrome). Set `--primary` to **Amplitude Blue** — light `#1e61f0`
(white text 5.22:1 AA), dark `#2c6bf0` (4.70:1 AA); `--ring` to blue for focus. Text/foreground and the
secondary/muted/accent chrome stay black/white/cool-gray (already neutral — matches Amplitude). One
secondary accent used for a single semantic purpose: `--destructive` = **Amplitude Red** (`#f23845`
light / `#ff5a5f` dark). No secondary accent used as general UI color.

**Chart palette — reloaded the dataviz skill first, re-validated, kept the CVD/contrast guarantee.**
Replaced the generic 6-hue rainbow with a blue-forward, cooler, Amplitude-flavored set: slot 1 =
**Amplitude Blue** (leads, "reinforces authorship"), then amber + teal (the warm/cool anchors CVD
separation requires), Amplitude **Violet** + **Pink**, and a cool **slate** as the gray-forward tertiary.
Light `#1e61f0,#e8a317,#12b5a6,#a373ff,#ff7d78,#4772b1`; dark re-stepped for the `#171717` surface
`#427ff7,#c88100,#00a48c,#9c72de,#d66363,#4881cc`. **Validated with the skill's script against this app's
real surfaces (light #ffffff, dark #171717): both modes PASS lightness band, chroma floor, adjacent CVD
ΔE, and normal-vision floor.** Documented trade-offs: (1) the dataviz chroma floor forbids a literal gray
series, so the "gray" is a cool slate at the minimum passing chroma — gray's primary chart role is
chrome/axes/ink per Amplitude; (2) slate sits at slot 6 not slot 2, because a gray-blue adjacent to the
blue lead fails the normal-vision separation floor; (3) contrast WARNs on the lighter warm hues are
relieved by the always-present legend + tooltip (identity never color-alone).

**Left intentionally:** `widget-message.tsx` warning tone keeps its hardcoded amber
(`text-amber-600 dark:text-amber-500`) — that's a semantic status color (filter-conflict / rate-limited),
a universal convention, not brand chrome or an old-palette reference; Amplitude's facts don't specify a
warning color, so changing it wasn't warranted.

**Verification:** `tsc --noEmit` PASS · `eslint .` PASS (0/0) · `next build` PASS (Poppins fetched) ·
`npm test` PASS (54/54). Visually reviewed both light and dark (Playwright screenshots, added ad-hoc and
removed): Poppins renders cleanly, Amplitude blue leads logo/CTA/active/primary-series, the four-country
chart is distinguishable and cooler in both themes. Docker image rebuilt (`docker compose up -d --build`):
container Up (healthy), all four smoke-test routes 200 on :3100. Committed + pushed to origin/main and
